#yocto-linux-iot

This is my working readme file which I maitain to go through my steps. This very informally maintained. 

TODO : Will keep on improving it.

Step 1: Create a github account.
Step 2: Install git package on Ubuntu system
Step 3: Set username and name for git publish on ubuntu system.
            git config --global user.email "tapan.kumarsahu@gmail.com"
            git config --global user.name "Tapan Kumar Sahu"
Step 4: Set a repository in github
Step 5. Clone the repo, modify, commit and push to Github -- Follow below steps for those
         https://www.earthdatascience.org/workshops/intro-version-control-git/basic-git-commands/
         

Created Repo -- yocto-linux-iot  --- for gateway project
                        https://github.com/swift26/yocto-linux-iot.git
                rainmaker-aws-iot -- For ESP32 devices.
                        https://github.com/swift26/rainmaker-aws-iot.git
                
Clone the initial copy from (Dunfell)
              git clone -b dunfell git://git.yoctoproject.org/poky.git 
                                or download from 
              https://www.yoctoproject.org/software-overview/downloads/archived-releases/



       1. Delete .git folder
       2. Make a new repo and do following step to push to Github
                rm -rf .git

	    git init
	    git add .
	    git commit -m "First Commit"
	    git remote add origin https://github.com/swift26/yocto-linux-iot.git
	                          
	    git remote -v
	    git push --set-upstream origin master
	    
	    
	    Above steps from : https://docs.github.com/en/github/importing-your-projects-to-github/importing-source-code-to-github/adding-an-existing-project-to-github-using-the-command-line
	    
      
      Next reading from below two sites
      https://lancesimms.com/RaspberryPi/HackingRaspberryPi4WithYocto_Part5.html
      https://jumpnowtek.com/rpi/Raspberry-Pi-4-64bit-Systems-with-Yocto.html
      
      3. Next step is to get the RasberryPI meta 
             
          git clone -b dunfell git://git.yoctoproject.org/meta-raspberrypi


      4. Get Openembedded meta (raspberry pi depends on openembedded meta)
      
              git clone -b dunfell git://git.openembedded.org/meta-openembedded
       


